basicInfo.description: The garden dahlia is a common spring flower that comes in a wide range of colors. The flowers themselves are unscented and attract pollinators, like bees, using only their bright coloration. Dahlia pinnata plants were grown by ancient Aztecs, and it is now the official flower of Mexico. It is genetically related to garden plants like sunflowers and zinnias.

distribution.habitat: Rich damp oak and pine woods
distribution.distributionSummary: Garden dahlia originates from Mexico, and due to its ornamental popularity it now grows in most of Europe as well as areas of Africa, Asia, and Central and South America. Its natural habitat is moist, rich woodland regions, mainly where oak and pine trees reside.

list.title: Economic Value
list.value: Garden Dahlia extract is used as a beverage condiment in Central America.

list.title: Garden Use
list.value: Garden dahlia is a perennial herbaceous plant commonly found in gardens. It is prized for its attractive late-summer blooming flowers. Its ornamental nature makes it suitable for mass planting, borders, and containers. Garden dahlia is appropriate for Cottage and Pollinator gardens. Plant with salvias, asters, and daylilies for color contrasts. Alternatively, planting with Coriander helps to deter aphids.

list.title: Interesting Facts
list.value: The garden dahlia is a world-famous flower with its gorgeous appearance. It has thick petals, which gives people an impression of grace and nobility, implying generosity, wealth and happiness. Some dazzling red flowers are especially magnificent and colorful, and can be chosen at major wedding venues or for birthdays of the elderly, which symbolizes long-term happiness. So, one meaning of the flower is good fortune and good health.

values: To commemorate the plant, the genus name Dahlia is evolved from the name of the Swedish botanist, Andreas Dahl. As the plant is widely planted in gardens, it is being known as the garden dahlia.

summarys.title: Water
summarys.value: Garden dahlia thrives in moist, mountainous regions, tolerating brief dryness. It requires moderate moisture, benefiting from watering every 1-2 weeks. As an herbaceous perennial, it flourishes outdoors with consistent soil moisture, avoiding both waterlogging and drought stress for optimal growth.

summarys.title: Fertilize
summarys.value: For garden dahlia, regular fertilization encourages healthy growth and flower production. Use balanced nutrients during the growing season and high phosphorus formulas pre-blooming, applying every 2-4 weeks. Seasonal changes affect needs; reduce in dormancy. Consider slow-release fertilizers for consistent nourishment.

summarys.title: Pruning
summarys.value: Garden dahlia thrives with early to late spring pruning, including the removal of dead stems for air circulation and disease prevention. Pinching young shoots encourages bushier growth, while cutting back spent flowers extends blooming. Regular pruning ensures better health and a more vibrant display.

summarys.title: Propagation
summarys.value: Garden dahlia can be effectively propagated through cuttings taken from healthy stems. Cut at a 45-degree angle below a leaf node, and optionally use rooting hormone. Place in well-draining soil, keep consistently moist, and provide indirect light until roots establish for successful growth.

summarys.title: Repotting
summarys.value: Garden dahlia requires exceptional drainage in containers to thrive, preventing water accumulation that can lead to root rot.
